lesson:
Lesson: Conditional Conformance
You can extend a generic type to conform to a protocol only under certain conditions—for example, when its type parameter also conforms to that protocol.

Core Concepts:
1. Logic Synthesis: Swift can synthesize requirements like '==' for you, but only if it knows that all properties (including those of generic type 'T') are also 'Equatable'.
2. Propagation: Conditional conformance allows protocols to propagate up through generic wrappers (like how 'Array' is Equatable if its elements are).

Example:
    struct Box<T> { let value: T }
    extension Box: Equatable where T: Equatable { }
    // Now you can compare Box(value: 5) == Box(value: 5)

Note: This is widely used in the Swift standard library for collections and wrappers.

