lesson:
Lesson: Computed Properties
Computed properties do not store a value. Instead, they provide a getter and an optional setter to calculate and manipulate other properties indirectly.

Core Concepts:
1. Getter: Code that runs when the property is read. It must return a value of the property's type.
2. Setter: Code that runs when the property is assigned a value. Swift provides the incoming value as a constant named 'newValue'.
3. Read-Only: If you only provide a 'get' block, the property is read-only.

Example:
    struct Square {
        var side: Double
        var area: Double {
            get { side * side }
            set { side = newValue.squareRoot() }
        }
    }

Note: Computed properties must always be declared as variables ('var') because their value can change.

