lesson:
Lesson: Static Methods in Extensions
You can add static methods to a type using an extension. This is commonly used to provide 'factory methods'—static functions that create and return a pre-configured instance of the type.

Core Concepts:
1. Factory Methods: Simplify object creation by providing named, standard configurations (e.g., 'Color.red').
2. Call Site: Because the method is static, you call it using the type name: 'Alloy.standard()'.
3. Type Return: These methods typically return an instance of the type being extended.

Example:
    struct Item { let id: Int }
    extension Item {
        static func first() -> Item { return Item(id: 1) }
    }

Note: This helps keep your primary struct definition focused on data, while moving helper logic into extensions.

